05806nam a22007815i 9781501767999DE-B159720240306010644.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2022017829  a97815017679997 a10.1515/97815017679992doi  a(DE-B1597)634555  a(OCoLC)1344378879  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aHC422b.M39 2023 4aHC422b.M39 2023 7aSOC0080202bisacsh04a338.95912231 aMcCarthy, Gerard, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOutsourcing the Polity :bNon-State Welfare, Inequality, and Resistance in Myanmar /cGerard McCarthy. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (282 p.) :b5 b&w halftones, 3 maps, 1 chart, 8 graphs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on Language, Usage, and Currency -- tIntroduction: Social Outsourcing and Inequality -- t1. Distributive Politics since Colonization -- tPart 1 AUTOCRATIC WELFARE CAPITALISM -- t2. Post-Socialist Welfare Outsourcing -- t3. Disasters and the Polity -- tPart 2 DEMOCRATIC WELFARE CAPITALISM -- t4. Democracy, Freedom, and Morality -- t5. Philanthropy and Wealth Defense -- t6. Self-Reliance and Entitlement -- tConclusion: Path-Dependence and Welfare Regime Change -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOutsourcing the Polity offers a new account of social outsourcing in post-independence Myanmar, demonstrating how the bankrupt post-socialist junta mediated market reform in the 1990s and 2000s and forced private and non-state actors to take the burden for social welfare. Informed by research during Myanmar's decade of partial civilian rule (2011–2021), Gerard McCarthy examines how ideals and practices of non-state welfare can both sustain democratic resistance and undermine social reform over time. Rather than expand government-led social action funded by direct taxation, grassroots activists and democratic leaders after 2011 variously framed government social action as ineffective, undesirable, and even corrosive of civic norms. They instead encouraged citizens to be "self-reliant" and support each other, including during disasters. Powerful tycoons filled the social gap, using public philanthropy to remake their reputations and to defend their ongoing expropriation of land and state assets from potential democratic redistribution. With non-state social actors more important than ever following Myanmar's return to dictatorship in 2021, Outsourcing the Polity casts new light on the lasting legacies of outsourcing for distributive politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPublic welfarexContracting outzBurma. 0aSocial servicexContracting outzBurma. 4aInternational Studies. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 70(DE-588)4018801-20(DE-627)1063239460(DE-576)208926593aFürsorge2gnd 70(DE-588)4020588-50(DE-627)1063175200(DE-576)208933956aGesellschaft2gnd 70(DE-588)4027058-00(DE-627)1062862340(DE-576)208968997aInnenpolitik2gnd 70(DE-588)4039349-50(DE-627)1062284470(DE-576)209034521aMilitärregierung2gnd 70(DE-588)4043649-40(DE-627)10620873X0(DE-576)209056975aOpposition2gnd 70(DE-588)4055879-40(DE-627)10615656X0(DE-576)209115742aSozialpolitik2gnd 70(DE-588)4056618-30(DE-627)1061543030(DE-576)209118288aStaat2gnd 70(DE-588)4112646-40(DE-627)1058356840(DE-576)209469684aAuswirkung2gnd 70(DE-588)4190021-20(DE-627)1041605430(DE-576)210063904aWirkung2gnd 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Asian Studies.2bisacsh  anon-state welfare, sociology of welfare, social outsourcing, capitalism in Myanmar, Myanmar resistance welfare, Myanmar oligarch